    <div id="general-intro" class="section-intro">
        <h1>Habit Formation 101</h1>
        <h4>Tips for the general reader</h4>
    </div>
    <div id="general-1" class="section">
        <div class="container">
            <div class="title-quote pull-right hidden-sm hidden-xs" style="margin-top:15px;"><strong>“Sow a thought, and you reap an act;<br/>
Sow an act, and you reap a habit;<br/>
Sow a habit, and you reap a character;<br/>
Sow a character, and you reap a destiny."</strong>
<div class="citation">― Samuel Smiles</div></div>
            <h1 class="section-title">1. Keep it Simple</h1>
            <div class="section-p">Simpler tasks become habits much more quickly than complex ones do
                <span class="citation">[1]</span>. In order to maximize the chance that you will follow through with your new habit, you want to start with simple behaviors.</div>

            <div class="section-p example">
                <h3>Example</h3>If you want to start a healthful exercising habit, you could start off just by walking. Every day, as soon as you get home, put on your walking shoes and begin. This simple behavior will become habit more quickly than a complex routine, such as driving to the gym and following a complicated fitness program.</div>

            <div class="references">
                <h4>Supporting References</h4>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <a href="http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1348/014466605X49122/full">Verplanken (2006) - Beyond frequency: Habit as a mental construct.
                            <em>British Journal of Social Psychology (45)</em>pp. 639-656</a>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="clearfix"></div>
    </div>

    <div id="general-2" class="section">
        <div class="container">
            <div class="title-quote pull-right hidden-sm hidden-xs" style="margin-top:35px;"><strong>"Motivation is what gets you started.<br/>Habit is what keeps you going." </strong><div class="citation">― Jim Ryun</div></div>

            <h1 class="section-title">2. Create an Environmental Context</h1>

            <div class="section-p">People are primed by
                <strong>cues in the environment</strong> to take certain actions
                <span class="citation">[1]</span>. If you want to perform a behavior more easily, specify a specific places where you are going to do this activity.</div>
            <div class="section-p">Deciding
                <em>where</em> to perform your habit will be more important than knowing
                <em>why</em> you want to do it
                <span class="citation">[2]</span>.</div>
            <div class="section-p example">
                <h3>Example</h3>If you want to drink more water, you could commit to drinking some water every time you enter your kitchen. The kitchen will serve as an environmental cue for you to perform your desired behavior.</div>

            <div class="references">
                <h4>Supporting References</h4>
