            <div class="title-quote pull-right hidden-sm hidden-xs" style="margin-top:35px;"><strong>"Enthusiasm is the electricity of life.<br/>How do you get it? You act enthusiastic until you make it a habit."  </strong><div class="citation">― Gordon Parks</div></div>
            
            

            
            
            <h1 class="section-title">3. Integrate into a Routine</h1>

            <div class="section-p">New behaviors that are consistently performed
                <em>after</em> a related activity, are more likely 18 months later to have become a habit
                <span class="citation">[1]</span>.</div>
            <div class="section-p">Whenever we have a behavioral routine, our brains create "event boundaries" around each action in that routine [2]. Whenever we complete one of these actions, moving across the event boundary, our brains are primed for the next related activity [3]. Because of this phenomenon, the best way to remember to perform a new behavior in the future is to start doing it after a related task.</div>

            <div class="section-p example">
                <h3>Example</h3>If you want to create a flossing habit, the best time to start flossing is right after you have brushed your teeth. Whenever you finish brushing your teeth in the future, you will be more likely to remember to floss.</div>

            <div class="references">
                <h4>Supporting References</h4>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <a href="http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.2044-8287.2012.02086.x/full">Judah, Gardner, & Aunger (2013) - Forming a flossing habit: An exploratory study of the psychological determinants of habit formation.
                            <em>British Journal of Health Psychology (18)</em>pp. 338-353</a>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <a href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3314399/">Zachs & Swallow (2007) - Event Segmentation.
                            <em>Current Directions in Psychological Science (16)</em>pp 80-84</a>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <a href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2819197/">Swallow, Zacks, & Abrams (2009) - Event boundaries in perception affect memory encoding and updating.
                            <em>Journal of Experimental Psychology: General (138)</em>pp. 236</a>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </div>
        </div>
