    </div>

    <div id="general-4" class="section">
        <div class="container">
            <div class="title-quote pull-right hidden-sm hidden-xs" style="margin-top:35px;"><strong>"Everything you are used to, once done long enough,<br/>starts to seem natural, even though it might not be."</strong><div class="citation">― Julien Smith, <em>The Flinch</em></div></div>
            
            <h1 class="section-title">4. Repeat the Behavior</h1>
            <div class="section-p">Try to perform the task at least
                <strong>once a day</strong>.</div>
            <div class="section-p">The more that you perform an action,
                <strong>the easier it gets to do it in the future</strong>, especially when performed in a specific context. This is because the brain creates "export neurons" that are designed specifically for the task
                <span class="citation">[1]</span>.</div>

            <div class="section-p example">
                <h3>Example</h3>Remember how I said that complex habitual behaviors can develop over time? Well, long-time chess players can perform some amazingly complex feats very easily and reliably. By practicing every day, they have developed efficient networks of neurons in their brains that quickly calculate future positions for each chess piece, for several moves ahead
                <span class="citation">[3]</span>. Some players are so good at this that they can do it for several different games at a time, all while blindfolded!</div>

            <div class="references">
                <h4>Supporting References</h4>
