    <div id="general-research" class="section-intro">
        <h1>Concepts for Habit Reasearch</h1>
        <h4>Concerns for the State of Habit Research</h4>
    </div>
    <div id="research-1" class="section">
        <div class="container">
            <h1 class="section-title">Problems of Control</h1>
            <div class="section-p">The greatest challenge facing habit research is controlling the rate of habit formation.</div>
            <div class="section-p">For example, in Lally, Van Jaarsveld, Potts, & Wardle's (2012) study on habit formation (published in the
                <em>European Journal of Social Psychology</em>, and cited by, according to Google Scholar, 123 academic articles), formation took between 18 and 254 days. High variance such as this can cause concern among researchers over the study's validity. Surely, if there had been adequate control over important factors in the study, variance would not be this high.</div>
            <div class="section-p">It is clear that sufficient care was not taken in the control of these factors. Participants did not have similar target behaviors, let alone repeating the tasks a similar number of times, or doing so in equivalent settings. Target behaviors ranged from "running for 15 minutes" to "eating a peice of fruit for lunch." The authors compared the study's data sets as if these were evidently comparable habits, without qualifying that assumption for the clarity of their audience. Why would <em>eating fruit</em> and <em>exercising</em> be comparable behaviors in a study to "model habit formation"?</div>

            <div class="section-p">The fault is not merely that of these particular researchers. After all, the current formation of habits, having changed since that of the behaviorists, is fairly new to social psychology. Not enough research has been done to qualify what the influencing factors are.</div>

            <div class="section-p">In an overview of the habit-formation literature, I found four direct influences and four indirect influences on formation, which all ought to be controlled during such research. They are as follows:</div>

            <div class="section-p">
                <strong>Direct influences</strong>
                <ol>
                    <li>Environmental Priming
                        <ul>
                            <li>Contextual cues prime and predict habit activation more powerfully than do intentions (Neal, Wood, Labrecque, & Lally, 2011)</li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                    <li>Repetition
                        <ul>
                            <li>The number of times that the subject performs the task has an effect on the rate of habit formation (Barnes, Kubota, Hu, Jin, & Graybiel, 2005; Verplanken, 2006)</li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                    <li>Complexity
                        <ul>
                            <li>Simple behaviors become habits more quickly than complex ones do (Verplanken, 2006)</li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                    <li>Routine Integration
                        <ul>
                            <li>Behaviors that fit into a routine of related actions, and that follow a related activity, are more likely to become habits 18 months later (Judah, Gardener, & Aunger, 2012; Verplanken, 2006; Williamson, Muller, Rea, & Thaw, 1999)</li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </div>

            <div class="section-p">
                <strong>Indirect influences</strong>
                <ol>
                    <li>Alcohol and stimulant abuse
                        <ul>
                            <li>The use of alcohol and stimulants has deleterious effects on the learning of new behaviors (Canales, 2010)</li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                    <li>Stress
                        <ul>
                            <li>Stress increases the subject's reliance of previous habits, making it less likely that new behaviors will become habits (Ferragud, et al., 2010)</li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                    <li>Diet
                        <ul>
                            <li>Numerous studies have shown the detrimental influence of fatty diets on hippocampal development of rats, and this is a concern for human participants as well (Lindqvist et al., 2006)</li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                    <li>Exercise
                        <ul>
                            <li>Exercise has consistently been found to effect the learning of new behaviors in rats and humans (Speisman, et al., 2013 )</li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </div>

